{| class="wikitable" |+ Ryūgakuji Kofun Cluster |- ! type !! Narita !! Sakae !! Total |- | {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=Domed|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} ({{nihongo|''empun''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}) || 19 || 52 || 71 |- | {{ill|Square Kofun|lt=Square|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} ({{nihongo|''hōfun''|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun}}) || 1 || 5 || 6 |- | [[Zenpokoenfun|Keyhole]] ({{nihongo|''zenpō-kōen-fun''|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|2=ja|3=前方後円墳|4=ko|5=전방후원분|6=zh|7=前方後圓墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|comement=second one attempting to fix this error|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}}) || 9 || 28 || 37 |- | TOTAL || 29 || 85 || 114 |- |}
Most of the tumuli are well preserved and more than 70 percent are located on prefectural lands. At present, the oldest is believed to be scallop-shaped Kofun No.101, which was constructed in the second quarter of the 6th century AD based on the type of ''[[haniwa]]'' discovered. The later mounds are concentrated in the northeast corner of the site, and include the Sengenyama Kofun, which is believed to be the last ''kofun'' built in Chiba Prefecture. From these dates, it is clear that the tumulus-building culture continued well after the introduction of [[:en:Buddhism in Japan|Buddhism]] to the area in the [[:en:Hakuho period|Hakuho period]] as evidenced by the nearby ruins of the [[:en:Buddhist temples in Japan|Buddhist temple]] of [[Ryūkaku-ji]]. Many of the tumuli are small, with a length of 20 to 30 meters in the case of keyhole-shaped tumuli, and a diameter of 10 to 20 meters in the case of many dome-shaped Kofuns.<ref name="Shiseki"/>
Some of the larger mounds were found to have more than one burial chamber, or had been reused for a subsequent burial some period after its original construction. ''Haniwa'' have been found only at 16 tumuli, but the majority of the tumuli remain unexcavated.
Artifacts recovered from the site are exhibited at the {{nihongo|'''Chiba Prefectural Bōsō Mura no Fudoki no Oka Museum'''|千葉県立房総のむら風土記の丘資料館|Chiba-kenritsu Bōsō Mura no Fudoki no Oka Shiryōkan}}. The site is a five minute walk from the Fudoki no Oka Kitaguchi bus stop on the Chiba Kotsu Bus from [[:en:Ajiki Station|Ajiki Station]] on the [[JR East]] [[Narita Line]]<ref name="Shiseki"/>
==Iwaya Kofun== The Iwaya Kofun is Kofun No. 105 in the cluster. It is a square-sided tumulus {{nihongo|''{{ill|Square Kofun|lt=hōfun|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun}}) and is the largest tumulus in the cluster. The tumulus is approximately 78 meters on each side, and is built in three tiers similar to a step pyramid, with a total height of 13 meters. Inside are two lateral-type stone-lined [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]]s constructed of blocks of soft limestone containing many fossilized shells. The tumulus has a double moat, enclosing an area measuring 108 meters east-to-west by 96 meters north-to-south. Since the entrance has been open since the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], no grave goods have been discovered.
